```

#### Step 2: Refactor UserService

```kotlin
class UserService(private val databaseService: DatabaseService) {
    fun getUser(userId: Int) {
        databaseService.getUser(userId)
    }

    fun createUser(name: String, email: String, phone: String, address: String) {
        databaseService.createUser(name, email, phone, address)
    }

    fun bulkUpdateUsers(updates: List<String>) {
        databaseService.bulkUpdateUsers(updates)
    }

    fun deleteUser(userId: Int) {
        databaseService.deleteUser(userId)
    }

    fun getUserAnalytics(startDate: String, endDate: String) {
        databaseService.getUserAnalytics(startDate, endDate)
    }
}
```

#### Usage

```kotlin
fun main() {
    val mysqlPool = MySQLConnectionPool()
    val postgresPool = PostgreSQLConnectionPool()

    val databaseService: DatabaseService = when (/* some condition */) {
        true -> MySQLDatabaseService(mysqlPool)
        else -> PostgreSQLDatabaseService(postgresPool)
    }

    val userService = UserService(databaseService)

    // Now you can use userService to perform user-related operations
    userService.getUser(1)
    userService.createUser("John Doe", "john.doe@example.com", "1234567890", "123 Main St")
}
```

### Summary

By extracting the database connection management into a separate service (`DatabaseService`), we adhere to the Single Responsibility Principle. The `UserService` is now solely responsible for user-related logic, and the database interactions are handled by the appropriate database service implementation. This separation of concerns makes the code more maintainable and testable.

